segments.text: But yeah, it's all set.
So you were born here in Texas, huh?
No, no, ma'am.
Go ahead.
It's fine.
I was born in Victoria, Texas in 1919.
You have been here a while.
At the end of this month.
So I'll be 57 years old.
And at age one, my family moved back to our home
the home country of Georgetown, Texas, which is in Wilson County.
Where's that?
I mean...
It's about 30 miles north of Austin.
And this central part of the state is rich in history in that the Chisholm Trail and a number of the other cattle drive routes went through that country because...
of the formation of the land.
If you follow Highway 81 South in North Texas, say, over down to Waco and on down to Georgetown, Austin, San Marcos, San Antonio, if you'll notice on the west side, there's mostly ranching land.
It's a pretty rough country, but right along that edge, there's a number of major streams that come off the Cap Rock in the high country there and go leading on into the Gulf.
And this is the lower flatlands that run through there.
And there's also that area is predominated by the black lands of Central Texas.
Yes, sir.
So this was a...
A favorite place around my hometown in Georgetown was a favorite place by the Comanche Indians.
And as a young person, we knew of a campground where they had congregated and oftentimes went over and waited to find a number of artifacts such as their head and things of this sort.
Was it your parents that decided to stay here, or did you have earlier ancestors?
My grandmother, my great-grandmother, came to Texas right after the Civil War.
And she was a crass widow, referred to in those days.
In other words, she and her husband had separated, but she had two young sons that she brought to Central Texas.
to join a family over there in that area by the name of Glascott.
And incidentally, the city of Georgetown is named after my great-great-uncle, who was a Mr. George Glascott.
And back in 1848, when the settlers around that part
And at that particular location, decided they wanted to build a town, and they needed some land to do it with.
Well, this Mr. George Laskar gave them a square mile of land.
And he said, the only requirement is that I'll give you the land provided you'll name it Georgetown.
But it later changed to Georgetown.
He's the only piece of history.
Right.
And so my family,
Mr. Glasscock and some of the other early settlers there received the land grants from not only the Spanish government, but they also received grants of land from the state in its early days.
And those lands were handed down to my grandfather and then to my father, who in turn, during the Depression, had the
divest themselves of them because of the, well, economic challenges.
Yes, sir.
Have you ever moved out of Texas?
Have you ever lived somewhere else?
Yes.
I, after graduating from A&M in 1940, I was commissioned second lieutenant infantry, and after nine months of work, I was called active duty and remained on active duty in the armed forces.
for 22 years and retired as a colonel.
And you've lived in a lot of different places, I'm sure.
Yes, it's been my privilege to serve in several overseas stations, such as Korea, Japan, Philippines, Germany, and in a number of states throughout the nation.
My father was an Air Force Lieutenant Colonel, and I myself have lived in the Philippines with him before.
different places.
What part of the Philippines were you in?
Manila.
We live in Quezon City.
Inside a compound, I guess is what you call it.
But you decided to move back here to Texas.
Well, of course, this was home.
The slogan is from Waco.
Most of our families live in the central Texas area.
So when I retired, I was
in Dallas at the time and was ready to go back to work for some.
And right after I retired, I was given, made an offer to come back to Texas A&M University to serve here on the staff.
And I've been here for 13 years as a member of the, I'm the director of student financial aid.
Well, I know where to come.
Do you enjoy your work?
Oh, yes, very much.
That's good.
It's a great place.
It's a great place to work.
Do you have a lot of relatives that are still living here in Texas?
No, we don't.
Our family consisted primarily of the great-grandmothers I referred to earlier, with two sons.
And one of the sons moved out into West Texas, and that part of the family just completely disappeared.
My grandfather had three sons, my father and the other son.
And they all passed on, and so there are some cousins that live in the area, but not a great number.
Yes, sir.
Well, I guess you've enjoyed your life here in Texas.
If you had a choice, would you live anywhere else now, or would you stay here, or a different part of Texas, maybe?
Well, that's hard to say.
I was very fortunate to have grown up in a small town like Georgetown, as you probably know.
Yes, sir.
The University of Southwestern.
This had a vital influence on the town.
The citizens are made up of a wide variety of persons of German extraction, Swedish, Polish, English, Scotch-Irish, and the Mexicans and Negroes.
And there was a real good mix of people there.
And it was a fine Christian town to have the influence of the university.
It helped the educational processes there.
Yes, sir.
And so, but it is not a place where you could make a fortune for a state.
You say you lived in Georgetown and then here and in Dallas.
Was there anywhere else that you lived since you were in Texas?
In Texas?
Well, I worked in Waco for a while.
And at one time during my career videos, I was a professor of military science in Texas.
And those are the only places that, well, after Mrs. Logan and I first married, we lived in Galveston for about 18 months.
And for that, while we were going out into other states and overseas.
What part of Texas did you

enjoy the most, and maybe there's another part that you haven't lived yet that you thought would be more enjoyable in the way of maybe geography or, you know, different parts of it that you might like to live there.
Oh, I don't know.
I think this area is just about as good a living area as you can find.
There's a good thing for each place.
Good thing to be said.
I do not like...
I guess it has.
That's a very good topic.
What kind of changes have you noticed since you first moved here?
when you were a cadet here to now in this area?
Well, when I was a cadet here, my senior year, we moved into the cadet dormitory.
That was the first year in 1939, the first year that area was occupied.
And that was what got us named the new dormitory.
And so we moved in there.
And we...
where Mosier and Kruger and Dunn and so forth buried.
You notice there's a horse barn there?
Yes, sir.
There was all this area to the south and east was cattle and horses and things of this sort.
And in the cadet corps, when we had field problems, we would start our field problem exercises, company platoon, battalion-sized field exercise.
We would have our starting point.
over where College View is now and come across that open grass area where the photo team practices and people get out and get golf shots and go on across what's now the golf course.
And this high point over here where we're sitting tonight in this wooded area was the enemy objective.
And this is where you'd wind up your exploration.
The movement of the front gate to the east side of the campus occurred about two years before 1936.
Most of the traffic that came to the campus came by way of Westgate.
And, of course, the railroad there and the railroad station were a focal point of interest.
You said, sir, that you were
In the class of 39, there was a veterinarian back in my hometown.
I don't know his first name.
I know his name was Dr. Davis.
He was kind of a well-built man in the way that he was pretty big.
And then there's another guy named Robert Cherry, who was the mayor of my hometown.
Do you remember those guys?
I remember Davis.
Now, my class is 40.
Of course, I regularly live in 40.
In our senior year, the first was the fall semester, wasn't it?
I graduated in 40, but I remember Davis.
Terry, I don't place right offhand, but I may.
If you have your old yearbook, you might be able to look him up.
He's about 6'1".
He's a well-built man.
He runs the main laundry back in my hometown in Jamaica.
Well, you said that the traffic was changed to the east side about two years before you got here.
How about the town here, Brian, College Station?
College Station here and there?
College Station, there was about three stores up there where Northgate is now.
It was down by the railroad, where the railroad underpass is.
Of course, now there was no underpass.
There was just a

the road just went up over the railroad and it's pretty rough crossing but on that corner was the gulf swimming station the principal garage and swimming station up above was a couple of grocery stores and and then the rest of it just uh warmly and there were a few few uh stores over around east gate a couple of there but uh that was the extent of it and uh
Actually there was a grocery store on campus, there was a barber shop, there was the soda fountain right there in the YMCA building, and there was a bowling alley and swimming pool in that area.
And so the laundry was here.
As I say, there was one garage, and that was it.
That's for both towns?
That was for college patients.
How about Bryan?
Now, Bryan was... Bryan started about where... Now, let's see.
Let's do landmark.
You know where...
where the Shamrock Station is on South College, that Y there.
Brian just about began there and went on into the main part, the business part of Brian, was down on Main Street.
And there used to be buses that you could ride.
I missed the trolley.
I didn't get to ride the trolley, but there were buses, and went back into it.
So there was kind of a...
A difference between the cities back then?
Oh, yeah.
Well, it was a distinct area.
In fact, there was quite a few good farms right in there.
Was that kind of the place to go?
Was there something to do in Bryan?
Oh, there was a couple of eating places downtown where you'd go down and you had money to purge and what have you.
Dominic's had a pretty good looking waitress.
I guess there just weren't that many girls at all back then anyway.
No, there were, but the only young ladies that were on campus were the professors' daughters and those who, daughters of the military people.
Now, of course, the professors and the military staff all lived on campus at the time.
In fact, Dean's Row was right there where the MSC is.
And there was a number of large homes there on that street that just faced the drill field where the MSC is.
And this was where we deemed the college, Dean Kyle, Dean Gilchrist, and Dean Gustafson, and then
There were several others, and where the trigon is now was where the confidant song was.
There was a large phone there, and John Moore had received a lot of attention because he had a very pretty view of the development of Francis.
So then you moved away from here.

in uh what 41 40 40. i lived here in 40 and we went off to the service i went to well i went to work in waco and i was there for nine months and then i called active duty went from there to galveston served in galveston for about two years and then was transferred up to north carolina
Georgia, and then overseas.
And then finally wound up in Japan and stayed there for almost three years before he came back and was stationed in New York City.
And then back to Georgia, and then to Germany, and then to Stephenville, Texas.
To Stephenville.
Then when was the, you moved back here 13 years ago, is that what you said?
What kind of, uh, did you visited a in between the time you were back to Stephenville?
I had been here one, one time when I was a military staff at Carlton State College.
Why?
There wasn't a meeting here and we came down and attended a
Okay, now that was after the time you returned to Stephenville?
Okay, so when you moved back here, then you should have noticed the big change.
What was your first impression when you came back here?
Well, the biggest change, of course, that I noticed was that
The Coke building was new.
There was no such thing as that.
There were several of the older buildings that were gone.
The MSC was new, or had been built since I was here.
And G. Riley White had been put in.
There had been some change to Kyle Field.
There were several dorms that had been built over in the Salugan dorm there in the south.
Northwest Department.
I didn't know that it was that first year that they let the civilians in.
I thought it was 64.
Actually, military science was first declared non-compulsory in about 1954, the first time.
And it was for about three years it was not compulsory in there.
You didn't have to be in the Corps.
But then they were in the board of directors reinstated again.
I don't remember how long it was.
But now when I came back here in 63, the court was not compulsion.
There was a size and no large number of students.
Of course, in my day, there was a lot of students that were not in the core really.
They wore the uniform, but they were not known as the Corps of Cadets.
They lived in the Corps because there was no place else to go.
Oh, I see.
They were called non-regs in our day.
Oh, and then we turn the term over to all civilian students on campus now.
I refer to you as non-regs by the people in the Corps.
When you came back here, was all the farmland between College Station and Bryan now pretty much gone?
Yes, it was pretty well gone.
There had been...
A lot of building take place in between here and Bryant, even in that short period of time.
There's been quite a few additions.
Of course, this area out south of here, when we first moved in here, there was only houses about three blocks south of us.
In that time, it's gone all the way past the west bypass
How about, you know, I noticed downtown Bryan is just kind of unique all by itself.
It's kind of an old addition now back on the, uh, about two streets off from now, the main street, I guess.
And then you have all the new, you know, everything, Denny's and things down on the other street.
Was that, uh, was that about the way it was when you were here in 63 or was it, uh,
The main street's still over there where all the old buildings were.
At that time, the only major shopping center outside of downtown Bryan was the Manor East Shopping Center.
What was that?
No, not Manor East.
What is the one where it's here?
Townshire.
Townshire was the only other major shopping center, and it had become very...
widely used.
But still, many of you have to go to downtown Bryan at that time.
There were more stores along North Gate over here.
And the Redmond Cherry Shopping Center had just been built.
It was new and just getting started.
Yes.
One of the things that my teacher has noticed about people that are now living in Texas
is that it seems like a lot of them were born here, moved away, and then returned here to retire.

And one of the questions she was asking us was to find out if the people we were interviewing would know any friends of theirs that would say moved away and moved back, and why this syndrome is for the people to move back to Texas to retire.
Is there something about it just being home?
Because there's a lot of other states that aren't known as home states, like maybe somewhere like
maybe California people might be born in California and then not really move back there too much, live in other places.
Well, if you've ever lived in other places, I think that's a good reason to come back.
There are some places like, oh, there's some beautiful places in Georgia and Oregon and Washington State that we seriously consider, particularly in Washington, Oregon,
I seriously consider moving to a retirement place.
Was that up in the mountains?
No, it's along the seacoast.
And it's fine climate and so on.
But I think one of the reasons is Texans are family oriented.
And the family still means a lot to many of us.
My mother was born here.
So we came back primarily with the idea that we had four children, and we wanted our children to know their grandparents, know their cousins, and the rest of the family, you see.
So we moved back into Texas.
Well, the Army was good to us.
Unfortunately, due to the assignment in my last four years, I was assigned to headquarters in Pentagon, Washington, but my duty station is in Dallas, Texas.
Oh, I see.
So when we got ready to retire, we were already located in the area that we were going to stay here.
My mother was born in Denison, Texas.
That's where I'm from.
I don't know if you know where that is.
All her family was born in Denison or in eastern Texas where the pine trees are.
And everybody is always in touch, you know, pretty much still.
And even when the third or fourth cousin of somebody dies, there's a big funeral and everybody goes down to it and still gets together for reunions down there.
Well, my father, his family live in southern Alabama in the German community because my last name is Dornstotter.
I hadn't realized you might be a good infection.
Oh, yeah.
Actually, it's a Dornstatter.
Yeah.
And they don't get together too much.
They know pretty much who's alive and who's not, but that's about it.
But I did notice that Texas was a big family community type thing.
People, even if their cousins live all over the city, they still know pretty much where everybody is and keep in touch.
Well, they...
Like Mrs. Logan's family, their name, they're scholars in Swiss German, German-Swiss.
They always have a family union on Labor Day, and they're quite a large family.
There's about 70 or 80 people that congregate, and it's quite a time.
I mean, even outsiders like me, I know everybody.
And this, I think, is one of the reasons that people come back to Texas.
And there's...
There is an honesty and an openness and a friendliness about people from Texas that I don't think we find in a lot of other places.
You haven't lived around the world, too.
It's something that we gained, I think, from a heritage from our forefathers who established this country.

personally a lot to do with it is there are many states that have the same type of area for the whole state because they're not very big, like in the New England countries, but in this state you can, as a resident, you can go from mountains to, you know, up in Dalhart where it snows all the time to, say, Galveston in South Texas, and you can go to about anywhere and find your type of climate that you pretty much want, except for maybe like an area like Oregon or Washington where the
they have a rough cold climate and the storms that are always coming through and things like that.
Well, it's the course of climate we deal with.
You have enough change in the seasons that it doesn't become very monotonous like you find out in Hawaii and other places like that.
So the climate, there is a lot of opportunity here in the state.
And then again, the family ties, I think,
And there's a feeling not only among Aggies, but also among Texans that, well, it's Texans against the world, so to speak.
Yeah, that was another big subject brought out where there's more of a unity here in Texas about us being Texans, that we relate to that all over.
People from California can do it a bit.
People from Alaska can do it some, and then maybe some people from Florida.
But here in Texas, it's just kind of the Alamo and, you know, everything that we're Texas and to hell with everybody else sometimes, you know.
Oklahoma does that some, too.
Oh, yeah.
We've got them pretty well trained.
We've had them for actually a quarter of a year, so we've not gotten good.
Yeah.
Well, the tape is just about over.
Is there anything you'd like to say that any impressions that have been made here
uh on by texas on you anything that you remember more than anything else no i don't i don't know of anything
And, you know, if you'd like to make any particular comment about it, as I say, I think it's a great place to hear that I'm fortunate in having my early life here.
I've been very fortunate in being able to serve my country in many places and in many fine assignments.
have the opportunity to come back and come to a place like Connors Place and touch in with some of the local, with young people, the way it's going to back on in.
So you're going to be welcome.
And in the past, I don't believe it's been much better.
